00:03:30.119 --> 00:03:39.639
data from clinical trials that are going on, and then also more experimental research

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:50.160
that's being done, either basic mechanism of action kinds of things or translational

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:56.240
research on the trials that we've already done. And that's what I often help with, is

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:02.880
people doing additional research questions on data from our clinical trials. And the

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:07.839
data that we have from clinical trials, it's designed for the clinical trial first and

00:04:07.839 --> 00:04:14.800
foremost. So the data that is going to be the primary outcome in a trial is really well

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:20.279
formatted, well curated, easy to work with. But experimental biomarkers, for instance,

00:04:20.359 --> 00:04:29.559
new assays that are just being developed, things like that, it's not as uniform in the

00:04:29.559 --> 00:04:36.040
format. And we often want to do analyses across multiple studies. And each of these clinical

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:41.160
trials is kind of its own thing with its own team, and so there can be significant differences

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:49.000
between them. So I help to do a lot of data harmonization, combining multiple clinical

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:57.640
trials together, solving differences in format, data cleaning issues, and then also trying

00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:02.839
to make decisions, like if there's an actual difference between the way an assay was done

00:05:02.839 --> 00:05:08.679
in study one versus study two, how do we combine that in a way that's still valid to analyze

00:05:08.679 --> 00:05:20.600
them together? It's a lot of the data cleaning, data wrangling work that I think there's a bad

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:28.440
reputation for it, but it's so, so important. And I get really excited about it and trying to

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:37.559
make the data that we already have higher quality, easier to use. And so I've done a lot of

00:05:37.559 --> 00:05:43.320
these data harmonization projects, and it's kind of the same things over and over again. Every project

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:51.079
you have to identify which columns are compatible between studies or data sources, figure out does

00:05:51.079 --> 00:05:57.720
the content match, do the units of measurement match, that kind of thing. And it's, every project

00:05:57.720 --> 00:06:02.920
is its own unique thing, but also there's so much repetition in the kinds of things that you're

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:09.880
doing. And so I'm really excited about ways to automate that. And so one thing that I've

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:17.959
been working on recently is a way to use LLM assistants for these data harmonization projects

00:06:17.959 --> 00:06:25.160
in a reproducible way. So a lot of the work that people are doing with data in LLMs,

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:29.640
it might be through something like DataBot and Positron, and you're having this interactive

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:34.679
conversation with your data. But then when you're done with that, it only works for that one

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:40.839
data set you were looking at, and it only captures exactly what you did in that session.

00:06:41.799 --> 00:06:49.079
So what I'm working on and what I'll talk about in my PositConf talk is a way to capture the output

00:06:49.079 --> 00:06:55.640
of an LLM into config files, specifying what kinds of data transformations do you need to do,

00:06:56.359 --> 00:07:01.720
what parts of your data sets that you're starting with are compatible with one another to be put

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:10.679
together into the same outputs. So capturing all of these steps into config files on a standard

00:07:10.679 --> 00:07:17.640
data model so that you can have the LLM work on the parts that it's good at, which is making these

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:25.000
config files, and then put it into a reproducible, deterministic pipeline,

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:29.160
and have that part do what it is good at, which is reproducibility.

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:36.920
This is one of the things that has made me most scared about LLMs in the past, is just like

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:40.600
we can't put them into a reproducible pipeline and expect them to do the same thing.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:45.959
So you are focusing on solving that problem and making it so that the LLM is creating

00:07:46.839 --> 00:07:51.880
the instructions for the work that you are doing, and those instructions are reproducible,

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:57.000
and you don't have to depend on the LLM to be a deterministic thing when it cannot be.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:01.160
I think that's amazing and interesting, and I can't wait to hear more from your PositConf talk.

